\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1}{\ignorespaces A large, beautifully rendered depiction of a right triangle with legs labeled $a = 3$ and $b = 4$ and hypotenuse $c = 5$. On each side of the triangle, a perfect square grid is constructed outward: a $3 \times 3$ grid of unit squares on the shorter leg (shaded in sky blue), a $4 \times 4$ grid on the longer leg (shaded in warm gold), and a $5 \times 5$ grid on the hypotenuse (shaded in soft coral). The $9$ blue tiles and $16$ gold tiles are visually rearranged --- an arrow or "explosion" diagram shows them fitting snugly into the $25$-tile coral square, confirming $9 + 16 = 25$. Beside the triangle, a small photograph-style rendering of the Plimpton 322 clay tablet, roughly palm-sized, covered in cuneiform numerals arranged in neat columns, with a caption reading "Babylon, c. 1800 BCE."}}{lvi}{figure.caption.2}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {subsection}{\numberline {0.1.1}A Four-Thousand-Year-Old Secret}{lvii}{subsection.0.1.1}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces A table of the first sixteen primitive Pythagorean triples, organized in four columns. Column 1: the triple $(a, b, c)$ with $a$ odd and $b$ even. Column 2: the Euclid parameters $(m, n)$ that generate each triple. Column 3: the value of $c - b$, highlighted in a pale yellow background. Column 4: the value of $c - a$, highlighted in pale green. The triples listed are: $(3,4,5)$, $(5,12,13)$, $(8,15,17)$, $(7,24,25)$, $(20,21,29)$, $(9,40,41)$, $(12,35,37)$, $(11,60,61)$, $(13,84,85)$, $(28,45,53)$, $(33,56,65)$, $(36,77,85)$, $(20,99,101)$, $(48,55,73)$, $(39,80,89)$, $(65,72,97)$. At the bottom, a note in italics reads: "Notice anything about the $c - b$ column?" The values in that column are $1, 1, 2, 1, 8, 1, 2, 1, 1, 8, 9, 8, 2, 18, 9, 25$ --- a sequence that repays close inspection.}}{lviii}{figure.caption.3}\protected@file@percent }
