\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.8}{\ignorespaces A map-style diagram of the Berggren tree's first three levels, drawn as a road network or subway map. Each "station" (node) displays the triple on a signpost. Each "line" (edge) is labeled L, M, or R. The path from root $(3,4,5)$ through $(21,20,29)$ to $(39,80,89)$ is highlighted in red, with the label \textbf  {ML} appearing as a route number. A compass rose in the corner gives the convention: L = left branch, M = middle branch, R = right branch.}}{59}{figure.caption.35}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.9}{\ignorespaces A visual "zoom" effect. On the left, the top of the Berggren tree is shown in full detail (three levels, all nodes visible). On the right, a telescope or "wormhole" graphic shows a single dramatic curved arrow labeled "$B_2^{1{,}000{,}000}$" leaping from the root directly to a node astronomically far down the middle branch, bypassing all intermediate nodes. The intermediate nodes are shown as a blur of receding dots, like stars during a hyperspace jump in a science fiction film. A small counter in the corner reads "20 matrix multiplications."}}{60}{figure.caption.36}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {3.7}The Elevator Going Up: Inverse Matrices and Tree Ascent}{61}{section.3.7}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.10}{\ignorespaces The Berggren tree from §2, but now with upward-pointing arrows drawn in a contrasting color (gold against the tree's green). The arrows are labeled $B_1^{-1}$, $B_2^{-1}$, $B_3^{-1}$. A highlighted path in bright red shows the "elevator ride" from $(39, 80, 89)$ up through $(21, 20, 29)$ to the root $(3, 4, 5)$. At each step, the inverse matrix used and the resulting triple are displayed in a small annotation box.}}{63}{figure.caption.37}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.11}{\ignorespaces A side-by-side display of $B_2$ and $B_2^{-1}$. Between them, the Lorentz adjoint formula $B_2^{-1} = \mathbf  {Q}\, B_2^\top \, \mathbf  {Q}$ is written in an elegant calligraphic font. Arrows show the three-step process: first multiply by $\mathbf  {Q}$ (which flips the sign of the third row/column), then transpose, then multiply by $\mathbf  {Q}$ again. The visual metaphor is a mirror reflection --- the inverse is the original matrix seen "from the other side of the looking glass."}}{63}{figure.caption.38}\protected@file@percent }
