\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.17}{\ignorespaces A full-page "map" of the chapter's conceptual landscape, drawn in the style of a medieval mappa mundi or a fantasy-novel treasure map. The map contains labeled regions: "The Broken Square" (a cracked stone tablet near the coast), "Berggren Forest" (a dense ternary forest of branching paths), "The Light Cone" (a mountainous volcanic peak with conical sides and lattice points glowing on its slopes), "Shortcut Wormhole" (a swirling portal connecting two distant points), "The Elevator" (a mineshaft with upward arrows), "Chebyshev Ridge" (a series of peaks growing exponentially taller), and "The Factoring Forge" (a smithy where numbers are being split on an anvil). Paths connect these regions, retracing the chapter's narrative arc. A compass rose in the corner points not to N/S/E/W but to "Algebra / Geometry / Analysis / Number Theory." The map is bordered with decorative flourishes and tiny Pythagorean triples hidden in the marginalia.}}{74}{figure.caption.44}\protected@file@percent }
