\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6.1}{\ignorespaces A large ornate bank vault door with seven distinct keyholes arranged in a circle. Each keyhole is labeled with a variable: $a_1, a_2, \ldots  , a_7$. In the center of the door is inscribed "$N$". Below the vault, a small equation: $a_1^2 + a_2^2 + \cdots  + a_7^2 = N^2$. Radiating lines connect each keyhole to the center, suggesting independent channels of attack. The vault is drawn in the style of a 19th-century bank, with rivets and brass fittings.}}{131}{figure.caption.76}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {6.2}A Menagerie of Pythagorean Creatures}{132}{section.6.2}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6.2}{\ignorespaces A "phylogenetic tree" of Pythagorean creatures, drawn whimsically like a naturalist's evolutionary diagram. At the bottom is the classic triple $(3,4,5)$ labeled "The Ancestor," drawn as a sturdy three-legged creature. Branching upward: quadruples (four legs), quintuplets (a five-armed starfish), sextuplets (a six-legged insect), and at the top, the octuplet --- a playful smiling octopus with eight tentacles. Each creature has its defining equation written on its body in small, elegant type. The tree branches are slightly organic and vine-like, giving the whole diagram the feel of an Enlightenment-era naturalist's plate.}}{133}{figure.caption.77}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6.3}{\ignorespaces A specimen catalog table, styled with elegant borders like a 19th-century naturalist's journal. Three rows for quintuplets: $(1,1,1,1,2)$, $(1,2,2,4,5)$, $(1,4,4,4,7)$; two rows for sextuplets: $(1,1,1,2,3,4)$, $(1,1,3,3,4,6)$; one row for octuplets: $(1,2,3,4,5,6,3,10)$. Each entry shows the tuple and a verification column with the sum-of-squares computation. A small checkmark appears beside each verified entry.}}{134}{figure.caption.78}\protected@file@percent }
