\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6.4}{\ignorespaces A circular "combination lock" diagram for $N = 15$. The outer ring shows the quadruple $(5, 10, 10, 15)$ with the three spatial components placed at equally-spaced points on the circle. Three arrows point inward from each spatial component to the center, labeled "$\gcd (15 - 5, 15) = 5$ {$\text  {$\mathsurround \z@ \mathchar "458$}$}", "$\gcd (15 - 10, 15) = 5$ {$\text  {$\mathsurround \z@ \mathchar "458$}$}", "$\gcd (15 - 10, 15) = 5$ {$\text  {$\mathsurround \z@ \mathchar "458$}$}". The successful channels are highlighted in green. A small "cracked safe" icon appears beside the factor $5$. The overall style recalls an antique pocket watch.}}{138}{figure.caption.79}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6.5}{\ignorespaces A similar lock diagram for $N = 21$, with the quadruple $(6, 9, 18, 21)$ and three channels shown: $\gcd (15, 21) = 3$, $\gcd (12, 21) = 3$, $\gcd (3, 21) = 3$. The winning factor $3$ is highlighted, and the complementary factor $7$ is shown in a smaller annotation. The lock is drawn slightly larger and more ornate than the $N = 15$ version, suggesting increasing sophistication.}}{139}{figure.caption.80}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {6.5}The Maze Run Backwards — Inside-Out Factoring}{140}{section.6.5}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6.6}{\ignorespaces A complete graph $K_7$ (seven vertices, all $21$ edges drawn) superimposed on a regular heptagonal frame. Each vertex is labeled $a_1$ through $a_7$ and drawn as a small keyhole shape. Each edge is labeled with a small "$\gcd $" symbol. The center of the heptagon contains "$N$" in large serif type. In one corner, a small legend: "7 vertices = 7 primary channels; 21 edges = 21 pairwise channels; total = 28 keys." The graph is drawn in deep blue ink on a parchment-colored background, evoking a Renaissance diagram.}}{141}{figure.caption.81}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {6.6}Sisyphus and the Number Theorist — Climbing and Falling}{142}{section.6.6}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6.7}{\ignorespaces Three panels side by side, showing inside-out factoring in increasing dimensions. Panel 1 (Triple): A 2D cross-section of a cone, with a single point labeled $N$ on the axis and one free parameter $u$ sweeping an arc. A single arrow labeled "1 channel" points from the arc to a factor. Panel 2 (Quadruple): A 3D cone, with $N$ fixed on the axis and two free parameters $u, v$ sweeping a surface (a disk inside the cone). Two arrows point outward, labeled "2 channels." Panel 3 (Octuplet): A stylized high-dimensional cone rendered as an abstract starburst, with $N$ at center and six radiating free-parameter axes, each labeled $u_1$ through $u_6$. Six arrows point outward, labeled "6 channels." Caption: "More dimensions, more freedom, more chances."}}{143}{figure.caption.82}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6.8}{\ignorespaces A maze shown from above, with a single winding path from START to FINISH. The start end is labeled "Search for tuples" and is colored in frustration-red. Next to it, the same maze viewed from the exit, with the solution path highlighted in green and obviously simple. The exit is labeled "Fix $N$, work backwards." Below, a mathematical caption: "The inside-out method: start with $N$, choose free parameters, check for integer solutions."}}{144}{figure.caption.83}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6.9}{\ignorespaces A rooted tree diagram with $(3, 4, 5)$ at the root. Three branches ascend to children: $(5, 12, 13)$, $(21, 20, 29)$, $(15, 8, 17)$. Each child has three children of its own, and so on for three levels, with actual Pythagorean triples labeling each node. The upward direction is labeled "ASCENT: Building tuples (easy)" in blue. A thick red arrow descends from a large triple near the leaves --- say $(697, 696, 985)$ --- all the way down through intermediate nodes to the root, labeled "DESCENT: Factoring (hard, but rewarding)." The hypotenuse values are printed in bold at each node along the descent path, visibly decreasing: $985 \to 493 \to 229 \to \cdots  \to 5$.}}{145}{figure.caption.84}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {6.7}The Hall of Mirrors — The Reflection $R_{1111}$ and the Quadruple Forest}{146}{section.6.7}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6.10}{\ignorespaces A "before and after" pair of Pythagorean quadruples, arranged as two tetrahedra. The left tetrahedron has vertices labeled $a$, $b$, $c$ (spatial, at the base) and $d$ (hypotenuse, at the apex). The right tetrahedron has the reflected values $d - b - c$, $d - a - c$, $d - a - b$ at the base and $2d - a - b - c$ at the apex. A curved arrow between them, labeled "$R_{1111}$", connects the two tetrahedra. The apex of the right tetrahedron is visibly lower (smaller) than the left, indicating descent. Below, three GCD expressions emerge from the spatial vertices of the right tetrahedron, each pointing toward a box labeled "Factor of $N$?"}}{147}{figure.caption.85}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {6.8}The Elevator Between Floors — Lifting, Projection, and Chain Composition}{148}{section.6.8}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {6.9}The Magic Trick That's 1,400 Years Old — Brahmagupta, Fibonacci, and Euler}{149}{section.6.9}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6.11}{\ignorespaces A cutaway building with floors labeled 3 through 8, one above the other. An elevator shaft runs through the middle. On Floor 3, the triple $(3, 4, 5)$ sits in a small room, drawn as a right triangle. An upward arrow labeled "Trivial Lift (insert $0$)" leads to Floor 4, where the quadruple $(3, 4, 0, 5)$ appears. A different upward arrow, labeled "Chain Lift", connects $(3, 4, 5)$ on Floor 3 directly to the quadruple $(3, 4, 12, 13)$ on Floor 4, with a note showing the intermediate chain through $(5, 12, 13)$. A downward arrow labeled "Peel" drops from a quintuplet on Floor 5 to a quadruple on Floor 4. Each floor is furnished differently --- Floor 3 has simple triangle decorations, Floor 8 has octopus-themed wallpaper. Caption: "The dimensional elevator: ride up to gain channels, ride down to simplify."}}{150}{figure.caption.86}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6.12}{\ignorespaces Two gears meshing together. The left gear has four teeth labeled "$a$", "$b$", "$a^2$", "$b^2$"; the right gear has four teeth labeled "$c$", "$d$", "$c^2$", "$d^2$". The output shaft below is labeled "$(ac - bd)^2 + (ad + bc)^2 = N_1 N_2$". The gears are drawn in a clean mechanical style, with visible cog teeth interlocking. Caption: "The Brahmagupta--Fibonacci identity is a multiplication machine for sums of squares."}}{152}{figure.caption.87}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6.13}{\ignorespaces A $4 \times 4$ grid showing the Euler four-square multiplication table. The rows are labeled $b_1, b_2, b_3, b_4$ and the columns $a_1, a_2, a_3, a_4$. Each cell contains the corresponding product term (with appropriate signs) from the $c_1, c_2, c_3, c_4$ formulas. The table is drawn in the style of a Renaissance multiplication table, with ornamental borders, flourishes, and a cartouche at the top reading "Euler's Quaternionic Table (1748)." Below, a small note: "The quaternion multiplication rule, disguised as a sum-of-squares identity."}}{153}{figure.caption.88}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {6.10}Where All Roads Meet — The Congruence of Squares}{154}{section.6.10}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {6.11}The Octopus's Garden — A Meditation on Dimension and Difficulty}{155}{section.6.11}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6.14}{\ignorespaces A Venn diagram with three large overlapping circles. The left circle is labeled "Pythagorean $k$-tuples", the right circle "Modern factoring algorithms (QS, NFS)", and the bottom circle "Congruences of squares." The triple overlap in the center is highlighted with a golden glow and labeled "The factoring sweet spot." Small arrows show the logical flow: $k$-tuples generate congruences, congruences are exploited by algorithms, algorithms factor numbers that generate new $k$-tuples. The diagram is drawn on a slightly aged parchment background.}}{156}{figure.caption.89}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6.15}{\ignorespaces A number line from $0$ to $N - 1$ showing the squaring map orbit: dots at positions $x, x^2 \bmod  N, x^4 \bmod  N, x^8 \bmod  N, \ldots  $, with arrows connecting successive values. Two dots at different positions $x_i$ and $x_j$ are highlighted in red --- they "collide" in the sense that $x_i^2 \equiv x_j^2 \pmod  {N}$. An arrow from the collision points to the equation "$\gcd (x_i - x_j, N) = $ nontrivial factor." The orbit eventually cycles, and the collision point is at the junction where the "rho" shape forms, evoking Pollard's rho method.}}{157}{figure.caption.90}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {6.12}Exercises}{158}{section.6.12}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6.16}{\ignorespaces An octopus in a garden of numbers, each tentacle reaching into a different "keyhole" in a giant composite number $N$ inscribed on a stone vault embedded in the ground. The octopus is smiling contentedly, with mathematical symbols floating gently around it like bubbles. Above it, the equation $a_1^2 + a_2^2 + \cdots  + a_7^2 = N^2$ floats like a thought bubble. The garden contains flowers shaped like the numbers $3, 5, 7, 11, 13$ (the prime factors being sought), growing among vine-like tendrils that trace the shapes of the Berggren tree branches. In the background, a faint grid of integer lattice points fades into the distance. Caption: "The octopus's garden: seven tentacles, twenty-eight channels, one happy factorer."}}{159}{figure.caption.91}\protected@file@percent }
