\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {11.1}{\ignorespaces A dramatic visual metaphor. A large integer $n = 8051$ is depicted as an ornate locked treasure chest, iron-banded and ancient. Two keys hover on either side: the left key is engraved with "$(x - y) = 83$" and the right key with "$(x + y) = 97$." Neither key alone fits the main lock, but a glowing golden operation labeled "$\gcd $" extracts a skeleton key from the left key that slides into the lock and opens the chest, revealing two smaller jeweled boxes inside labeled "$83$" and "$97$." The equation $x^2 - y^2 = (x - y)(x + y)$ is inscribed in flowing script on the lid of the chest.}}{267}{figure.caption.152}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {11.2}{\ignorespaces A worked numerical "factor-o-gram" table with five columns: $x$, $y$, $x^2 - y^2$, "Divisible by $n$?", and $\gcd (x - y, n)$. Six rows of attempts are shown: the first four rows show failed attempts with red crosses (either the difference is not divisible by $n$, or the GCD yields the trivial values $1$ or $n$). The fifth row is highlighted in gold with a green checkmark, showing $x = 90$, $y = 7$, $x^2 - y^2 = 8051$, "Yes!", and $\gcd (83, 8051) = 83$. A small annotation reads: "The factors are $83$ and $97 = 8051 / 83$."}}{268}{figure.caption.153}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {11.2}Why the Trick Works — The Algebra of Shared Factors}{269}{section.11.2}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {11.3}{\ignorespaces A Venn-diagram-style figure. Two large overlapping circles are labeled "Prime factors of $(x - y)$" (left) and "Prime factors of $(x + y)$" (right). The prime factors of $n$ are shown as colored dots: a red dot labeled $83$ sits in the left circle only, and a blue dot labeled $97$ sits in the right circle only. The overlap region is empty. An annotation reads: "$n \mid (x-y)(x+y)$ means every colored dot appears in at least one circle." A second annotation below: "$n \nmid (x-y)$ means NOT all colored dots are in the left circle." A third annotation: "$\gcd (x - y, n)$ harvests exactly the colored dots in the left circle --- the factor $83$."}}{270}{figure.caption.154}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {11.3}Fermat's Method and Its Magnificent Slowness}{271}{section.11.3}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {11.4}{\ignorespaces A historical portrait sketch of Pierre de Fermat in his judicial robes and white collar, quill in hand, seated at a desk. A leather-bound copy of Diophantus's \textit  {Arithmetica} lies open beside him. In the book's margin --- rendered in a cramped but legible hand --- he has written a column of trial computations: "$32^2 - 1009 = 15$" ({$\times $}), "$33^2 - 1009 = 80$" ({$\times $}), "$34^2 - 1009 = 147$" ({$\times $}), "$35^2 - 1009 = 216$" ({$\times $}), each with a small cross beside it. At the bottom of the column, in slightly larger script: "$\text  {Hanc marginis exiguitas non caperet.}$" A candle gutters on the desk.}}{272}{figure.caption.155}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {11.5}{\ignorespaces A horizontal number line with $\sqrt  {n}$ marked at center. Two scenarios are drawn above the line. In Scenario A ("balanced factors"), two dots labeled $p$ and $q$ sit close to $\sqrt  {n}$ on either side, connected by a short arc labeled "Fast convergence." In Scenario B ("unbalanced factors"), $p$ sits far to the left (near the origin) and $q$ far to the right (near $n$), connected by a long arc stretching across the entire line, labeled "Slow convergence --- as bad as trial division." A rueful face emoji decorates Scenario B.}}{273}{figure.caption.156}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {11.4}The Smooth Criminal — Numbers With Only Small Sins}{274}{section.11.4}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {11.6}{\ignorespaces A "smoothness spectrum" chart. A horizontal axis shows integers from $1$ to $100$. Each integer is represented by a vertical bar whose height equals its largest prime factor. Numbers that are $7$-smooth (largest prime factor $\leq 7$) are colored bright green; $11$-smooth numbers are blue; $13$-smooth are yellow; and rough numbers (largest prime factor $> 13$) are red. The green bars cluster densely near the left end but grow sparser toward the right. A horizontal dashed line at height $7$ marks the "$B = 7$" smoothness boundary. Notable numbers are labeled: $64 = 2^6$ (a tall green bar at height $2$), $97$ (a towering red bar, being prime), $96 = 2^5 \times 3$ (green, height $3$).}}{275}{figure.caption.157}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {11.7}{\ignorespaces A whimsical cartoon showing two characters on a hillside. On the left, a friendly, round, smiling boulder labeled "$120 = 2^3 \times 3 \times 5$" rolls easily down a gentle slope, leaving a smooth track behind it. On the right, a jagged, angular, grimacing rock labeled "$127$ (prime)" is stuck halfway down the hill, wedged between two outcroppings. A sieve --- a large mesh screen --- sits at the bottom of the hill, and the smooth boulder has passed through easily while the jagged rock is caught in the mesh. Caption: "Smooth numbers roll through the sieve; rough ones get stuck."}}{276}{figure.caption.158}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {11.5}The Factor Base — Assembling Your Arsenal}{276}{section.11.5}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {11.8}{\ignorespaces A visual "arsenal rack," drawn as a polished wooden display case with $k = 6$ labeled compartments, one for each prime in $\mathcal  {F}(13)$: "$2$", "$3$", "$5$", "$7$", "$11$", "$13$." Below the rack, the number $360 = 2^3 \times 3^2 \times 5$ is "decomposed" into colored balls dropped into the compartments: three red balls in the "$2$" slot, two blue balls in the "$3$" slot, one green ball in the "$5$" slot, and the remaining three slots ($7$, $11$, $13$) are empty. A second decomposition shows $1{,}001 = 7 \times 11 \times 13$: one orange ball in "$7$," one purple ball in "$11$," one gold ball in "$13$," and the first three slots empty. The two numbers' vectors are written underneath: $(3,2,1,0,0,0)$ and $(0,0,0,1,1,1)$.}}{278}{figure.caption.159}\protected@file@percent }
