\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {12.7}{\ignorespaces A small tetrahedron with vertices labelled $(1, 2, 2, 3)$ sits beside a geometrically similar but three-times-larger tetrahedron labelled $(3, 6, 6, 9)$. Dotted lines connect corresponding vertices. A label beneath reads: "$\gcd (3, 6, 6, 9) = 3$: scale factor extracted."}}{307}{figure.caption.174}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {12.7}The Imaginary Witness}{307}{section.12.7}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {12.8}{\ignorespaces A three-dimensional integer lattice (a grid of dots in space) with a translucent sphere of radius $d$ centred at the origin. Two lattice points on the sphere are highlighted in red and blue, with their coordinates labelled. Dashed lines drop from each point to the three coordinate axes. Along the arcs of the sphere connecting the two points, the expressions $(a_1 - a_2)(a_1 + a_2)$, $(b_1 - b_2)(b_1 + b_2)$, and $(c_2 - c_1)(c_2 + c_1)$ are annotated, showing how the lattice pair identity links the two points.}}{308}{figure.caption.175}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {12.8}The Prime Inquisitor}{309}{section.12.8}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {12.9}{\ignorespaces The complex plane with an integer grid. A vector from the origin to the point $(2, 3)$ is drawn boldly, representing the Gaussian integer $2 + 3i$. A square of side length $\sqrt  {13}$ is constructed on this vector, with area $= 13$ labelled inside. Beside it, a rectangle of dimensions $1 \times 13$ (corresponding to $d - c = 1$, $d + c = 13$ for the quadruple $(2, 3, 6, 7)$) is drawn with the same total area, shaded identically. A prominent equals sign connects the two shapes. Caption: "Same area, different shapes --- the Gaussian norm meets the difference of squares."}}{310}{figure.caption.176}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {12.9}The Mod Squad}{311}{section.12.9}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {12.10}{\ignorespaces An Archimedes-style lever diagram. A beam balances on a triangular fulcrum labelled "Euclid's Lemma." On the left end of the beam sits the product $(d - c)(d + c)$; on the right, a weight labelled with the prime $p$. An arrow from $p$ branches into two paths: one pointing to $(d - c)$ labelled "$p$ divides this..." and the other pointing to $(d + c)$ labelled "...or this." The fulcrum is the logical principle that forces the choice.}}{312}{figure.caption.177}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {12.10}The Number Cruncher's Workbench}{313}{section.12.10}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {12.11}{\ignorespaces A $4 \times 4$ grid where rows represent values of $a^2 \bmod  4$ (labelled $0$ and $1$, repeating) and columns represent $b^2 \bmod  4$. Each cell contains two sub-cells for the two possible values of $c^2 \bmod  4$. Cells where $a^2 + b^2 + c^2 \equiv 0$ or $1 \pmod  {4}$ are shaded green (valid); cells with sum $\equiv 2$ or $3$ are shaded red (forbidden). The overall pattern has a striking checkerboard structure, and a caption reads: "The modular filter --- green cells admit Pythagorean quadruples, red cells do not."}}{314}{figure.caption.178}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {12.12}{\ignorespaces A mathematician's workbench scene. A wooden desk is strewn with papers showing the four showcase quadruples, pencil stubs, and a magnifying glass poised over the collision identity. A chalkboard in the background displays the parametric machine. On the desk sits a vintage Curta mechanical calculator, its counter dials reading "$\text  {GCD} = 3$." A steaming cup of coffee anchors one corner, and a cat sleeps on a stack of Jacobi's collected works.}}{315}{figure.caption.179}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {12.13}{\ignorespaces A histogram (bar chart) showing the number of primitive Pythagorean quadruples for each value of $d$ from $1$ to $50$. Bars for prime values of $d$ are coloured blue; bars for composite values of $d$ are coloured red. The visual pattern reveals that composite values tend to have more representations --- taller red bars, shorter blue bars --- the very asymmetry that makes the factoring method possible. Caption: "More representations, more collisions, more factors."}}{316}{figure.caption.180}\protected@file@percent }
