\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {13.8}{\ignorespaces Two squares side by side, the first partitioned into sub-rectangles showing $a^2 + b^2$, the second showing $c^2 + d^2$. An arrow labeled "$\times $" points to a third, larger square partitioned \textit  {two different ways} into sums of two squares: $(ac - bd)^2 + (ad + bc)^2$ on one diagonal half and $(ac + bd)^2 + (ad - bc)^2$ on the other. Caption: "Brahmagupta's magic: one product, two decompositions."}}{329}{figure.caption.188}\protected@file@percent }
