\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {16.4}{\ignorespaces The first four levels of the Berggren tree, drawn as an elegant ternary tree diagram on cream paper. Root node: a small right triangle drawn to scale inside a circle, labeled $(3,4,5)$. First generation: three circles containing right triangles for $(5,12,13)$, $(21,20,29)$, and $(15,8,17)$, connected to the root by branches labeled $A$, $B$, $C$ respectively. Second generation: nine circles with their triples. Third generation: hints of twenty-seven further nodes fading into a misty background. Each triangle is drawn to approximate scale, so the triangles grow more elongated or squat as the numbers change. The overall shape suggests an infinite fractal canopy.}}{390}{figure.caption.222}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {16.5}{\ignorespaces A side-by-side comparison. LEFT: A Minkowski spacetime diagram showing a light cone opening upward and downward from the origin, with two events marked on the upper cone connected by a curved arrow labeled "Lorentz boost." The familiar hyperbolic grid lines of a boosted reference frame are visible. RIGHT: The Berggren tree drawn on the Poincaré disk model of the hyperbolic plane, with each primitive Pythagorean triple plotted as a point and the three Berggren transformations acting as hyperbolic isometries, tiling the disk. Caption: "The same group acts on both pictures."}}{392}{figure.caption.223}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {16.5}Climbing Down the Tree: The Inverse Matrices and Descent}{393}{section.16.5}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {16.6}The Highway of Pure $A$'s: Consecutive Parameters and Depth}{394}{section.16.6}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {16.6}{\ignorespaces A vertical "elevator" diagram. The triple $(697, 696, 985)$ is at the top floor. At each floor below, an inverse Berggren matrix is applied (labeled with which inverse, $A^{-1}$, $B^{-1}$, or $C^{-1}$), and the resulting triple is shown alongside its hypotenuse, prominently displayed in a box. The hypotenuse shrinks at every floor: $985 \to \cdots  \to 5$. At the bottom: $(3, 4, 5)$ with a triumphant flag. The path of inverse operations, read from bottom to top, spells out the Berggren address.}}{395}{figure.caption.224}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {16.7}The Depth of a Prime: A Number-Theoretic Surprise}{396}{section.16.7}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {16.7}{\ignorespaces A portion of the Berggren tree showing only the "A-highway" --- the leftmost branch at every generation, drawn as a long straight road receding into one-point perspective. Each node is a signpost showing the triple and its $(m,n)$ parameters: $(2,1) \to (3,2) \to (4,3) \to (5,4) \to (6,5) \to \cdots  $. The $B$- and $C$-branches veer off to the sides at each node like exits on a motorway, partially visible but fading into the distance. The road stretches to the horizon, conveying the infinite nature of the path.}}{397}{figure.caption.225}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {16.8}{\ignorespaces A vertical number line on the left showing primes $5, 7, 11, 13, 17, 19, 23, 29, 31, \ldots  $ in ascending order. Horizontal arrows of increasing length connect each prime to its depth on a scale at right: $1, 2, 4, 5, 7, 8, 10, 13, 14, \ldots  $. The arrows form a staircase pattern, and the visual relationship --- depth grows linearly with $p$ --- is immediately apparent. A dashed line with slope $1/2$ and intercept $-3/2$ is superimposed, fitting all the arrow endpoints exactly.}}{398}{figure.caption.226}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {16.8}How Many Triples Does a Number Have? The Semiprime Surprise}{398}{section.16.8}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {16.9}{\ignorespaces A "multiplication table" style grid. Rows labeled with the four small-factor divisors of $225$: $1, 3, 5, 9$. Columns labeled with their complementary large factors: $225, 75, 45, 25$. In each cell, the resulting Pythagorean triple is drawn as a small right triangle with sides labeled. The four triangles fan out like a hand of playing cards. The two primitive triples are drawn in bold ink; the two imprimitive ones in lighter, dashed lines, with their scaling factors ($\times 3$, $\times 5$) noted.}}{400}{figure.caption.227}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {16.10}{\ignorespaces A bar chart showing $|T(N)|$ for $k = 1, 2, 3, 4, 5$ distinct odd prime factors. The bars grow exponentially: $1, 4, 13, 40, 121$. Each bar is decorated with tiny right triangles to convey the count visually. The curve $y = (3^k - 1)/2$ is superimposed as a smooth dashed line.}}{401}{figure.caption.228}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {16.9}Tiling the Hyperbolic Plane}{401}{section.16.9}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {16.11}{\ignorespaces A Poincaré disk tessellation in the spirit of Escher's \textit  {Circle Limit III}. Instead of fish, each tile contains a right triangle with its side lengths printed inside. At the center: a large tile containing the $(3, 4, 5)$ triangle. Radiating outward in three directions (corresponding to the $A$, $B$, $C$ branches): first-generation tiles containing $(5,12,13)$, $(21,20,29)$, $(15,8,17)$, then second-generation tiles with their nine triples, growing smaller toward the boundary. The three branching directions are rendered in three distinct colors --- blue for $A$, red for $B$, gold for $C$. The tiles shrink exponentially toward the disk boundary, and the outermost tiles are tiny but still contain legible (if minuscule) triple labels. The overall effect is of infinite mathematical richness contained within a finite circle.}}{403}{figure.caption.229}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {16.10}The Grand Unification: Pythagoras Meets Einstein}{404}{section.16.10}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {16.12}{\ignorespaces A full-page "Grand Diagram." At the center, a right triangle labeled $(a, b, c)$ with a small square at the right angle and $Q = 0$ inscribed inside it. Radiating outward in four directions from the triangle: (NORTH) the Berggren tree, spreading upward like a canopy, its first three levels visible; (EAST) the Minkowski light cone, opening rightward with grid lines of boosted reference frames; (SOUTH) a factorization lattice showing divisor pairs $d \times e = a^2$ connected by lines, with Pythagorean triples at the nodes; (WEST) the Poincaré disk tessellation, with the triangle's triple at the center tile. Curved arrows labeled with the key identities connect all four quadrants: "$M^\top J M = J$" between the tree and the cone; "$de = a^2$" between the cone and the lattice; "hyperbolic isometry" between the tree and the disk; "null vector" between the disk and the cone. The entire diagram is framed with a thin border, and at the very bottom, in small italics: "One equation, four worlds."}}{405}{figure.caption.230}\protected@file@percent }
