\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {16.13}Nine Faces of One Equation}{409}{section.16.13}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {16.13}{\ignorespaces An aged Egyptian rope-stretcher sits on a limestone block beside the Nile at dusk. His apprentice stands beside him, gesturing at the sky, where the stars have rearranged themselves into a web of glowing connections --- a ternary tree, a light cone, a lattice grid, a tower of algebras, a quantum circuit --- all radiating outward from a single bright triangle formed by three stars: the constellation of Pythagoras. The Nile reflects the geometry in shimmering, distorted form.}}{410}{figure.caption.232}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {16.14}The Unreasonable Effectiveness of a Schoolchild's Equation}{413}{section.16.14}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {16.15}The Puzzles That Remain}{413}{section.16.15}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {16.14}{\ignorespaces A full-page "Rosetta Stone" mandala. At the center, carved into an ancient stone tablet, is the equation $a^2 + b^2 = c^2$. Nine spokes radiate outward, each ending in an iconic vignette: (1) a ternary tree with golden nodes, (2) a spacetime light cone with a photon streaking along its surface, (3) a zigzag path through a 2D lattice labeled "Euclid," (4) a grid of lattice points in 3D with a short vector highlighted in red, (5) a padlocked safe with a key labeled "$\gcd $," (6) a vertical tower of four floors labeled $\mathbb  {C}$, $\mathbb  {H}$, $\mathbb  {O}$, $\mathbb  {S}$ with the top floor cracked, (7) a quantum circuit with a Grover oracle magnifying glass, (8) a piecewise-linear tropical curve on a palm-tree island, (9) a torn parchment margin with Fermat's famous note in Latin. The nine spokes form a geometric rose window, with each pane colored distinctly. Around the outer rim, in small elegant type, runs the text: "Every theorem in this book is a consequence of, or a generalization of, this single line."}}{414}{figure.caption.233}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {16.16}A Last Puzzle}{415}{section.16.16}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {16.15}{\ignorespaces The final image. A single $3$-$4$-$5$ right triangle, drawn in clean black ink on an otherwise empty white page. At the right-angle vertex, a tiny door stands ajar, and through it spills warm golden light. The light illuminates, faintly, the outlines of vast mathematical structures receding into the distance --- trees, lattices, cones, towers, circuits --- all contained, impossibly, within the interior of the triangle. Beneath the triangle, in small italic type: \textit  {"The simplest objects in mathematics hide the deepest structures."}}}{417}{figure.caption.234}\protected@file@percent }
